\begin_layout Subsection
Imports for export
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The demand for imports for export is modeled exactly as domestically produced exports above:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
X^{m}_{x,t}=\mu^{Xm}_{x,t}q^{x}_{t}q^{\text{Scale}}_{t}\left(R^{Xm}_{x,t}\right)^{\eta^{X}_{x}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
except that the relative price 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{Xm}_{x,t}$
\end_inset

 is a static relation which only differs from 1 in the case of taxation of goods in transit.
 The foreign price competing with imports for export is simply the price of imports (see the chapter on price setting),
 and the relative price in the Armington equation for imports for export is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
R^{Xm}_{x,t} & =\frac{p^{Xm}_{x,t}}{\sum_{s}\mu^{m}_{x,s,t}P^{M}_{s,t}}\\
\\ & =\frac{\sum_{s}\mu^{m}_{x,s,t}P^{M\tau}_{d,s,t}}{\sum_{s}\mu^{m}_{x,s,t}P^{M}_{s,t}}\\
\\ & =\frac{\sum_{s}\mu^{m}_{x,s,t}\left(1+\tau^{M}_{x,s,t}\right)P^{M}_{s,t}}{\sum_{s}\mu^{m}_{x,s,t}P^{M}_{s,t}}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
While the numerator and denominator look very similar,
 the tax rate 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau^{M}_{d,s,t}$
\end_inset

 can be important for some 
\begin_inset Formula $(x,s)$
\end_inset

 pairs and may vary over time.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Derivation of the dynamic price ratio
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Derivation-of-price-ratio"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider the demand for exports given by the Armington equation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
X_{t}=\mu Q_{t}\left(\frac{\overline{P}^{X}_{t}}{P^{F}_{t}}\right)^{-\eta}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{P}^{X}_{t}$
\end_inset

 is the price of exports faced by foreign consumers and 
\begin_inset Formula $P^{F}_{t}$
\end_inset

 is the price of competing foreign products.
 We now introduce intermediaries (located abroad) that buy Danish exports at price 
\begin_inset Formula $P^{X}_{t}$
\end_inset

 and sell these exports to their consumers at the price 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{P}^{X}_{t}$
\end_inset

.
 With free entry and no additional costs we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{P}^{X}_{t}=P^{X}_{t}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Assume now that intermediaries face monopolistic competition and have an adjustment cost of setting their price.
 The optimization problem becomes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\overline{P}^{X}_{t}=\arg\max_{p_{i,t}}\left[p_{i,t}-P^{X}_{t}\right]X_{t}\left[\frac{p_{i,t}}{\overline{P}^{X}_{t}}\right]^{-\eta}-\left[g_{t}+\beta_{t+1}g_{t+1}\right]
\]

\end_inset

The first order condition of each intermediary is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
X_{t}\left[\frac{p_{i,t}}{\overline{P}^{X}_{t}}\right]^{-\eta}\left(1-\eta\left[p_{i,t}-P^{X}_{t}\right]\frac{1}{p_{i,t}}\right)-\left[\frac{\partial g_{t}}{\partial p_{i,t}}+\beta\frac{\partial g_{t+1}}{\partial p_{i,t}}\right]=0
\]

\end_inset

and imposing symmetric equilibrium 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i,t}=\overline{P}^{X}_{t}$
\end_inset

 this writes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\overline{P}^{X}_{t}=\frac{\eta}{\eta-1}P^{X}_{t}-\frac{1}{\eta-1}\frac{\overline{P}^{X}_{t}}{X_{t}}\left[\frac{\partial g_{t}}{\partial p_{i,t}}+\beta\frac{\partial g_{t+1}}{\partial p_{i,t}}\right]
\]

\end_inset

The expression shows that one can have zero (or close to zero) markups (the difference 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{P}^{X}_{t}-P^{X}_{t}$
\end_inset

) without having perfect competition.
 On the other hand,
 as 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta\rightarrow+\infty$
\end_inset

 we do have that 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{P}^{X}_{t}=\rightarrow P^{X}_{t}$
\end_inset

 (perfect competition implies zero markups).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There is also an adjustment cost in the expression above and is defined as the following:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
g_{t}\equiv\frac{\hat{\psi}}{2}\left[\frac{p_{i,t}/P^{F}_{t}}{p_{i,t-1}/P^{F}_{t-1}}-1\right]^{2}\overline{P}^{X}_{t}X_{t}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Defining the price ratio 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{R}_{t}=\overline{P}^{X}_{t}/P^{F}_{t}$
\end_inset

 and imposing symmetry yields
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\overline{R}_{t}=\frac{\eta}{\eta-1}\frac{P^{X}_{t}}{P^{F}_{t}}-\frac{1}{\eta-1}\frac{\overline{R}_{t}}{X_{t}}\left[\frac{\partial g_{t}}{\partial p_{i,t}}+\beta\frac{\partial g_{t+1}}{\partial p_{i,t}}\right]
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial g_{t}}{\partial p_{i,t}}=\hat{\psi}\left[\frac{\overline{R}_{t}}{\overline{R}_{t-1}}-1\right]\left[\frac{\overline{R}_{t}}{\overline{R}_{t-1}}\right]X_{t}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial g_{t+1}}{\partial p_{i,t}}=-\frac{\overline{P}^{X}_{t+1}}{\overline{P}^{X}_{t}}\frac{\partial g_{t+1}}{\partial p_{i,t+1}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Multiply by the factor 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\eta-1}{\eta}$
\end_inset

 to obtain the expression:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
R_{t}\equiv\frac{\eta-1}{\eta}\overline{R}_{t}=\frac{P^{X}_{t}}{P^{F}_{t}}-\frac{1}{\eta-1}\frac{R_{t}}{X_{t}}\left[\frac{\partial g_{t}}{\partial p_{i,t}}+\beta\frac{\partial g_{t+1}}{\partial p_{i,t}}\right]
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and define the auxiliary variable
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Psi^{Xy}_{t}\equiv\frac{1}{\eta-1}\frac{R_{t}}{X_{t}}\frac{\partial g_{t}}{\partial p_{i,t}}=\underbrace{\psi^{Xy}}_{\frac{\hat{\psi}}{\eta-1}}R_{t}\left[\frac{R_{t}}{R_{t-1}}-1\right]\left[\frac{R_{t}}{R_{t-1}}\right]
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
we obtain the expression for the price ratio
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
R_{t}=\frac{P^{X}_{t}}{P^{F}_{t}}-\Psi^{Xy}_{t}+\beta\frac{P^{F}_{t+1}}{P^{F}_{t}}\frac{X_{t+1}}{X_{t}}\Psi^{Xy}_{t+1}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
After having derived the dynamic relationship determining the price ratio we will comment some of the variables from above.
 Going back to the initial demand function we can see that using the 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{t}$
\end_inset

 ratio is equivalent to redefining the scale parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
X_{t}=\underbrace{\left[\frac{\eta}{\eta-1}\right]^{\text{\ensuremath{-\eta}}}\mu}_{\mu^{Xy}}Q_{t}\left(R_{t}\right)^{-\eta}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mu^{Xy}=\left[\frac{\eta}{\eta-1}\right]^{\text{\ensuremath{-\eta}}}\mu
\]

\end_inset

as well as redefining the adjustment cost parameter
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\psi^{Xy}=\frac{\hat{\psi}}{\eta-1}
\]

\end_inset

The value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta$
\end_inset

 is not separately identifiable which implies we cannot judge how competitive the intermediary price setting market is.
 Irrespective,
 what matters is that the problem is well specified for any finite value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta>0$
\end_inset

,
 and for any large value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta$
\end_inset

 we have that 
